1.2 Background

1.2.1 Some terminal-ology

  • computer hardware: physical elements of a computer

  • computer software: instructions which tell computer hardware how to perform a task

  • application software: a division of computer software; software which uses the computer system to perform functions beyond the basic operation of the computer itself

  • system software: a division of computer software; software used to manage computer hardware behavior and provide a platform for other software to run

Figure 1: Differences between hardware, system software, and application software (Neeraj Mishra)

  • operating system (OS): a division of system software; system software that manages computer hardware and software resources and provides common services for computer programs. Examples include Microsoft Windows and macOS.

  • kernel: component of an operating system; software at the core of a computer’s operating system which is used to mediate access to the computer’s resources

  • central processing unit (CPU): electronic circuitry within a computer which is responsible for running or executing programs; CPUs carry out the instructions of a computer program by performing the basic arithmetic, logic, controlling, and input/output (I/O) operations specified by the instructions

  • CPU core: the processing unit of a CPU

  • thread: thread of execution; an ordered sequence of instructions that tells the computer what to do

Figure 2: Components of a CPU (Daniel López Azaña)

  • random-access memory (RAM): a form of computer data storage which stores data and machine code that are currently being used

  • Unix shell: also known as a shell; a command-line interpreter that provides a command line user interface for Unix-like operating systems

  • terminal emulator: also known as a terminal; a text-based interface for typing commands, allowing users to interact with a Unix shell

  • graphical user interface (GUI): a form of user interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices through graphical icons and visual indicators

Figure 3: the Galaxy GUI, which provides a GUI for many bioinformatics tools (Wikipedia)

  • command-line interface (CLI): a means of interacting with a computer program where the user (or client) issues commands to the program in the form of successive lines of text (command lines)

1.2.2 What are Linux/Unix?

Unix is a family of operating systems that descend from the original Unix, which was developed in 1969 by Ken Thompson, Dennis Ritchie, Douglas McIlroy, and Joe Ossanna at AT&T’s Bell Laboratories in the United States (Ritchie, 1984, AT&T Bell Laboratories Technical Journal). In 1984, Bell Labs began distributing Unix as a proprietary product which users were not allowed to modify. Unix operating systems with which you may already be familiar are Apple’s macOS and Darwin (a component of what is now known as Apple’s macOS).

In 1983, Richard Stallman began the GNU Project with the goal of creating a completely free Unix-compatible software system (in Stallman’s own words: “Once GNU is written, everyone will be able to obtain good system software free, just like air.”). By 1990, nearly all of the major components of a GNU operating system were finished; however, one important piece was still missing: the kernel, which is where Linus Torvalds comes in. In 1991, while attending the University of Helsinki, Torvalds created a kernel which would later be released as the Linux kernel in 1992. By combining Linux with the GNU system, a fully functioning operating system was born. GNU/Linux, or Linux, refers to this family of free, open-source, Unix-like operating systems based on the Linux kernel. Popular Linux distributions include Ubuntu, Debian, and Red Hat.

Figure 4: Tux the penguin, the Linux mascot (Wikipedia)

For this workshop, we will be doing nearly all of our computing in a Linux environment because

  1. It’s free!
  2. Bioinformaticians have and continue to rely heavily on Linux; a significant proportion of the software, tools, and piplines for analyzing next-generation sequencing (NGS) data are written specifically for Linux/Unix systems and can only be run from the Linux/Unix command line
  3. An increasing number of web tools and desktop applications with graphical user interfaces (GUIs) are available for analyzing bacterial NGS data. However, even if you never, ever use Linux again, you will have a better understanding of what is going on “under-the-hood” for many of these applications

1.2.3 What is Bash?

Bash (Bourne-Again shell) refers to a Unix shell (a command-line interpreter that provides a command line user interface for Unix-like operating systems) and command language. It was written by Brian Fox for the GNU Project, with a beta version released in 1989. Since then, it has become the most popular Linux shell, as it is the default interactive shell for users on most Linux and macOS operating systems (which is why we will be using it for this workshop!). Bash allows users to type commands in a specific language, which the computer then executes.

1.2.4 The Linux File System

Before we start, it’s important to understand the structure of the Linux file system so we can navigate it from the command line.

If you’re a Windows user, you may be familiar with a file system that looks something like this:

Figure 5: Windows GUI (TechRepublic)

Mac users might understand their file systems as something that looks like this:

Figure 6: Mac GUI (O’Reilly)

The Linux file system isn’t so different; some popular Linux distributions, such as Ubuntu, might even have a very nice GUI, like the one below:

Figure 7: Ubuntu GUI (Me, IT and Tech)

However, when working from the command line, our view won’t be so pretty. But even without a GUI, we can imagine the underlying structure of the Linux file system as something resembling an upside-down tree, like the image below:

Figure 8: The Linux File System (LinuxPlanet)

Files, such as text files, image files, fastq files, fasta files, etc. are inside of directories. Directories are just another name for what one might call a “folder” in the Windows or Mac worlds. In the tree above (Figure 8; courtesty of LinuxPlanet), directories have green boxes around them, while files don’t.

If you look at the top of the tree (Figure 8), you’ll see a directory called the root directory, denoted by a forward slash (/). You can think of the root directory as the trunk of a tree from which all branches (paths) start.

One important thing to note before we begin is the difference between absolute paths and relative paths, which can be a frustrating concept for Linux command-line beginners. Paths are used to specify a particular file or directory; the full path, or absolute path to a file or directory starts from the root, /, and follows the branches of the files system, with each directory separated by a slash (/), until the file or directory of interest is reached. For example, in the tree above (Figure 8), if our file of interest is fluffy.jpg, the absolute path to fluffy.jpg is /home/sue/Pictures/pets/fluffy.jpg (just follow the shaded green boxes!). A relative path, on the other hand, specifies the path to a directory or file relative to another; usually, this is the directory you are currently in, also known as the working directory. So, for example, in the picture above (Figure 8), if we are currently inside the home directory, the relative path to fluffy.jpg is sue/Pictures/pets/fluffy.jpg (see how we didn’t start with a forward slash? That’s because we didn’t start at the root directory). If we move to the Pictures directory, our relative path to fluffy.jpg is pets/fluffy.jpg. Finally, if we move to the pets directory, the relative path to fluffy.jpg is just fluffy.jpg! However, the absolute path to fluffy.jpg remains /home/sue/Pictures/pets/fluffy.jpg.

Figure 9: Actual image of fluffy.jpg? (tommy.thecat.2015)

Also, note that paths, file names, and directories are case-sensitive. For example, in the image above, if you search for fluffy.jpg at the following path /home/sue/pictures/pets/fluffy.jpg, Bash will throw an error saying that your file doesn’t exist. Why? Because the actual path is /home/sue/Pictures/pets/fluffy.jpg, where the Pictures directory has a capital “P”. If you don’t type the path correctly, Bash will look for a directory named pictures within /home/sue/, which doesn’t exist.

Finally, note that you should try to avoid naming files and directories with special chacters, particularly whitespace, slashes, asterisks, and other special characters. You’ll notice that bioinformaticians love underscores and dashes, so consider using those instead of hitting the space key when you’re naming a file or directory!

2.1 Access the remote workstation

First, we need to connect to a remote computer with a Linux operating system. This process is different for Windows and macOS users, so follow the instructions for your operating system.

2.1.1 Windows Users

Windows users will need to download an SSH client (a software program which uses the secure shell protocol to connect to a remote computer or server). The steps below will explain how to download and use PuTTY, which is one such SSH client (but if you already have a favorite SSH client for Windows, feel free to skip this step and use that!)

  1. Download PuTTY for Windows

  2. Follow the instructions for installing PuTTY on Windows

  3. Double-click the PuTTY icon to run it (or find PuTTY from the Windows Start menu in the bottom left corner of the screen, and click to run it).

  4. In the box labeled “Host Name (or IP address)”, enter the computer’s IP address (lfs-rdl-fsc-869.landfood.ubc.ca) and click “Open”

  5. Type in your password (don’t be alarmed when you don’t see any characters when you are typing…that is supposed to happen!) and hit “Enter”

Congrats! You’re in!

2.1.2 macOS Users

Mac users will use the native SSH client (a software program which uses the secure shell protocol to connect to a remote computer or server).

  1. Open your terminal by holding the Command and Space keys, typing “Terminal” into the Spotlight Search bar, and pressing Enter

  2. Type the following command into your terminal, replacing myUsername with your own user name, and press Enter:

    ssh myUsername@lfs-rdl-fsc-869.landfood.ubc.ca

  3. When prompted, type your password (don’t be alarmed when you don’t see any characters when you are typing…that is supposed to happen!), and press Enter

Congrats! You’re in!

2.2 Navigating in a Linux Environment

Now that we’re connected to our Linux workstation, let’s learn some simple commands which will help us navigate the Linux directory structure.

  1. Let’s get the path to our working directory, i.e., figure out which directory (folder) we are currently in; to do this, we will use the pwd command (print working directory). To run pwd, type the following command below, and press Enter:
pwd

You should see the following text displayed, where myUsername is replaced with your own user name: /home/myUsername

We are currently in our home directory!

  1. Now, just for fun, let’s familiarize ourself with some simple commands which we can use to tell us information about our computer. Type each of the following commands (each outlined by a box) into your terminal, and press Enter after each to see what happens.

hostname prints the system host name:

hostname

whoami prints who you are logged in as (your user name):

whoami

date prints the current date and time:

date

cal will show this month’s calendar:

cal
  1. Now let’s see how much free and used memory we have, using the free command:
free

That’s a lot of numbers!

What happens when we add the -h option after free?

free -h

It makes the output much easier to read!

Luckily, we don’t need to memorize which options are available for which commands. To see this information (and much, much more), we can look at the manual for a particular command using the man command. Let’s take a look at the manual for the command free:

man free

Take a quick scroll through the manual for the free command using your up and down arrow keys. According to the manual, adding the -h option makes the output human-readable, as -h is the short form of the --human option.

Another useful option for free is --help.

Once you’ve gotten an idea of what a manual for a command looks like, you can exit by pressing q.

What do you think will happen when we run the following command?

free --human

Hopefully, you’ll see that the output of this command is identical to that produced using the free -h command we ran above.

Additionally, according to the manual for free, we can print a simple help message for free by including the --help option. Let’s see what happens when we try that:

free --help

Whenver we need to look up what a command does, how to run it, and what options are available to use with it, we can look at the manual using the man command or the --help option…even man has its own manual!

man man

To exit, press q.

  1. Now that we have an idea of how to run some simple commands and, more importantly, where we can go for help (often man or --help), let’s try to navigate within the Linux environment.

We’ll start by taking a look at everything in our working directory (which, as we know when we used the command pwd to print our working directory, is our home directory).

We’ll do this using the ls command, which lists the contents of a directory. When we don’t supply a path to ls, it will list the contents of our working directory (i.e., the directory we are currently in: our home directory!):

ls
  1. Just for fun, let’s create a new directory within our home directory named hello. We can do this by using the mkdir command (make directory), and supplying a path and name for our new directory, which in our case here will just be hello:
mkdir hello
  1. Now, let’s move to our new directory, hello. We can change directories by using the cd command and supplying the path to the directory into which we want to move (in our case, we want to move to the hello directory that we just created within our working directory):
cd hello
  1. How do we know if we changed directories? Use pwd to print our working directory!
pwd

We should see that we’re no longer in our home directory; now we’re in hello!

  1. Now that we’re in our new directory, hello, let’s practice copying a file into our new directory using the cp command.

To use cp, we need to supply the path to the source file, which we want to copy, as well as the path to the destination directory (where we want to copy the file to).

Let’s copy a text file named hello.txt to our current working directory (the hello directory which we are now in).

For this workshop, all of our files are stored in a directory named /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/.

Let’s take a look at what is inside our wgs_workshop directory. To do so, we can use ls and supply the full path to the wgs_workshop directory:

ls /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop

We should see several directories inside of wgs_workshop, each named after the activity.

The file we want for this activity, hello.txt, is located in the activity1_1 directory within the wgs_workshop directory. Let’s double check this by using ls command to list the contents of activity1_1:

ls /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1

We should see hello.txt listed!

Let’s copy hello.txt to our current directory, hello. To do this, we use cp, the path to hello.txt (/home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1/hello.txt), and the path to our directory, hello (/home/myUsername/hello, where myUsername is your own username):

cp /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1/hello.txt /home/myUsername/hello

If we type ls (to list the contents of our current directory), we can see that hello.txt is now in our current directory!

ls

If we type ls and supply the path to the activity1_1 directory (to list the contents of the activity1_1 directory), we will see that hello.txt still exists in that directory:

ls /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1

We just made a copy of the original file and stored it in our hello directory.

  1. In addition to copying files, we can also move them using the mv command. To practice this, let’s create a new directory within hello called ubc. We do this using mkdir and supplying the path and name of our new directory. Because we are already in hello, we can just supply the relative path (i.e., the new name) of our new directory (i.e., ubc):
mkdir ubc

Let’s move hello.txt to our new directory, ubc, by typing mv, the path to hello.txt, and the path to ubc:

mv hello.txt ubc

If we type ls, we’ll see that our working directory, hello, now only contains ubc:

ls

And if we type ls and supply the path to ubc, we’ll see that hello.txt is now in ubc:

ls ubc
  1. mv can also be used to rename files and directories. Let’s move hello.txt out of ubc and back into our hello directory. Additionally, let’s rename hello.txt to goodbye.txt.

We can do this with a single command in which we call mv to move the file, supply the path to the file we want to move/rename (ubc/hello.txt), and then supply the path to the directory to which we want to move the file, as well as a new name for the file (/home/myUsername/goodbye.txt):

mv ubc/hello.txt /home/myUsername/hello/goodbye.txt

If we type ls to list the contents of our working directory, we see that we now have a file named goodbye.txt in our current directory:

ls

If we type ls and supply the path to ubc (to list the contents of ubc), we will see that ubc is now empty:

ls ubc
  1. Let’s delete goodbye.txt because we don’t need it anymore. To do this, we use the rm command and supply the path to the file that we want to delete:
rm goodbye.txt

If we type ls to list the contents of our current directory, we see that goodbye.txt has been deleted:

ls

Importantly, be extra cautious when deleting files with rm! Once they are gone, they are gone forever.

  1. Now we know some simple commands for copying, moving, renaming, and deleting files, as well as for creating and changing directories. To set up for our first analysis, let’s rename our hello directory to something more meaningful, like activity1.

If we type pwd to print our working directory, we should see that we are still inside of the hello directory that we created:

pwd

To rename hello to activity1 , we first need to move up a level, out of our hello directory using the cd command. There are a couple of ways we can do this.

The first way, we supply the full path to our home directory, which is the directory one level up from hello: cd /home/myUsername

However, this is super annoying to type! Another way we can move up a single level is to use .. as our path, which is a shortcut that refers to the directory one level up from the working directory (in this case, our home directory): cd ..

A third way uses another shortcut; the tilde symbol, ~, is a shortcut to your home directory. Try typing the following to move to your home directory:

cd ~

If we type pwd, we will see that we are back in our home directory:

pwd

And if we type ls to list the contents of our current directory, we will see hello listed as a directory within our current directory (our home directory):

ls

Now, let’s rename hello to activity1 using mv, the path to hello, and the path to and desired new name of our directory (activity1):

mv hello activity1

If we type ls to list the contents of our current directory, we will see that hello is now activity1:

ls

If we type ls and supply the path to activity1, we will see that activity1 is empty, except for the ubc directory we created:

ls activity1
  1. Let’s get rid of the empty ubc directory within our activity1 directory because we don’t need it anymore. To do this, we can use the rm command with the -d option (which allows us to delete empty directories), supplying the path to our empty ubc directory:
rm -d activity1/ubc

Is the path we supplied to our empty ubc directory a relative path, or is it an absolute path? (Hint: the answer is in section 1.2.4 above!)

If we type ls and supply the path to activity1, we’ll see that activity1 is now empty:

ls activity1

2.3 Assessing the quality of raw Illumina reads with FastQC

  1. Now that we’re getting the hang of the command line, let’s analyze some genomic data! Let’s first move into our activity1 directory:
cd activity1

If we type pwd, we will see that we are now inside of activity1:

pwd

If we type ls, we will see that our current directory (activity1) is empty:

ls
  1. In the workshop directory, there are raw reads associated with a bacterial isolate. All we know is that the isolate was sequenced using an Illumina platform using paired-end reads with a Nextera library preparation, and that it came from a Salmonella enterica isolate.

If we type ls to see what’s in the /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1 directory, we’ll see that there are two files ending in .fastq.gz. These are the raw Illumina reads associated with our mystery isolate, Mystery Salmonella A: mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz contains the forward reads, while mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz contains the reverse reads. Both of these files are in fastq format (.fastq), compressed using gzip (.gz; a common method for compressing genomic data).

Let’s copy the forward reads into our current directory (/home/myUsername/activity1) using the cp command:

cp /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1/mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz ~/activity1/

Remember ~? It’s a shortcut for our home directory! (/home/myUsername)

If we type ls, we should see our forward reads in our current directory:

ls

Using the ~ in place of the path to our home directory shortens what we have to type; however, we can do even better! The . symbol stands for the path to our current directory, /home/myUsername/activity1. Let’s take advantage of this by copying the reverse reads to our current directory:

cp /home/labinstructor/wgs_workshop/activity1_1/mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz .

If we type ls, we’ll see that we now have forward and reverse reads in our current directory:

ls

Figure 10: fastq format (USEARCH)

  1. Now let’s run FastQC, a popular program that is used to assess the quality of sequencing reads. It will provide us with a lot of interesting and valuable metrics which can help guide our downstream analyses (e.g., read length, number of reads, per-base quality, adapter content). Here, we will use FastQC to assess the quality of the raw reads of our mystery isolate.

Figure 11: Output of FastQC (Babraham Bioinformatics)

The general format for running FastQC from the command line is as follows (note: don’t execute this command; it is just an example):

fastqc </path/to/first_reads.fastq.gz> </path/to/second_reads.fastq.gz> </path/to/third_reads.fastq.gz> </path/to/nth_reads.fastq.gz>

We will call the program (perl /opt/FastQC/fastqc), and we will supply the path to all of the reads we want to analyze, each separated by a space character.

Let’s try running FastQC with our forward and reverse reads. Because they are already in our current directory, we can just supply the names of the files:

perl /opt/FastQC/fastqc mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz

Once FastQC is finished, we can type ls and see that we now have four additional files: a .zip and a .html file for our two .fastq.gz files with our forward and reverse Illumina raw reads:

ls
  1. We are interested in looking at the html files, which contain FastQC’s quality assessment for our reads. Because we want to see all of the nice graphics in these html files, we’re going to need to copy them over to own computers. For this, we’ll use the secure copy protocol (SCP), which is a way to securely transfer computer files between a local host (our own computer) and a remote host (the computer on which we’ve been running our analyes).

For Windows users:

You can use a file transfer client such as WinSCP or FileZilla. If you haven’t already downloaded and installed one on your own computer, do so now. In both cases, to transfer files, you supply the IP address/name of the remote computer we’ve been working on, type in your password, and use the GUI to select which files you want to transfer. Here, you can select the two FastQC html files: /home/myUsername/activity1/mystery_salmonella_A_1_fastqc.html and /home/myUsername/activity1/mystery_salmonella_A_2_fastqc.html. Transfer them to the directory of your choice on your own computer.

For macOS/Linux users:

Mac users will use the scp command.

E. When prompted, type your password (don’t be alarmed when you don’t see any characters when you are typing…that is supposed to happen!), and press Enter

2.4 Trimming raw Illumina reads with Trimmomatic

  1. Now that we have a general idea of what the quality of our raw reads is like, let’s see if we can do better by cleaning up our raw reads. To that end, we’ll use Trimmomatic to trim our Illumina reads (i.e., remove Illumina adapter sequences and low-quality bases from our Illumina reads). Trimming can often improve read quality and, later, assembly. There are numerous trimming programs available (e.g., AdapterRemoval v2, Trim Galore/cutadapt, and bbduk, just to name a few), but here we will use Trimmomatic; it is a popular, fast, and relatively easy-to-use trimming program that, importantly, takes into account read pairing information for paired-end reads (most modern trimming software, including the Trimmomatic alternatives listed, should do this, but it’s always good to double-check beforehand if you try out something new).

Here, we will use Trimmomatic to:

A. Trim Illumina adapters left over from the Nextera library preparation

B. Use a sliding window approach to measure average quality within a 4-base window, trimming when the average per-base quality drops below a Phred quality score of 15

C. Remove trailing bases (i.e., bases at the end of a read) which drop below a Phred quality score of 3

D. Remove leading bases (i.e., bases at the start of a read) which drop below a Phred quality score of 3

E. Remove reads less than 36 bp in length (note that employing a minimum read length filter like we are doing here can be especially important for analyses which require counting of mapped reads, such as RNA-Seq)

Let’s get trimming! Back in your terminal, make sure you are in your activity1 directory with the forward and reverse reads from our Mystery Salmonella A isolate (mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz and mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz):

pwd

should show that we are in our activity1 directory

ls

should show mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz and mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz

(If not: cd /home/myUsername/activity1)

The command to run Trimmomatic for paired-end Illumina reads takes the following form (note: don’t execute this command; it is just an example):

java -jar trimmomatic-0.39.jar PE -phred33 -trimlog log.txt input_forward.fq.gz input_reverse.fq.gz output_forward_paired.fq.gz output_forward_unpaired.fq.gz output_reverse_paired.fq.gz output_reverse_unpaired.fq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:adapters-PE.fa:2:30:10 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:36

For this command, we are:

  • Calling Trimmomatic (java -jar trimmomatic-0.39.jar)
  • Telling Trimmomatic that we have paired-end (PE) reads (PE)
  • Telling Trimmomatic that our Illumina reads have ASCII_BASE 33 quality scores and not the ASCII_BASE 64 quality scores used by very old Illumina platforms (-phred33)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to create a log file named log.txt (-trimlog log.txt)
  • Giving Trimmomatic the path to our forward reads in fastq.gz format (input_forward.fq.gz)
  • Giving Trimmomatic the path to our reverse reads in fastq.gz format (input_reverse.fq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed forward read pairs that it outputs (output_forward_paired.fq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed forward unpaired reads that it outputs (output_forward_unpaired.fq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed reverse read pairs that it outputs (output_reverse_paired.fq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed reverse unpaired reads that it outputs (output_reverse_unpaired.fq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove any Illumina adapters, with the adapter sequences provided in the adapters-PE.fa file (ILLUMINACLIP:adapters-PE.fa:2:30:10)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove leading low quality or N bases below quality 3 (LEADING:3)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove trailing low quality or N bases below quality 3 (TRAILING:3)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to scan each read with a 4-base wide sliding window, cutting when the average quality per base drops below 15 (SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to drop reads less than 36 bases long (MINLEN:36)
  1. Let’s run Trimmomatic by typing in the following (very long!) command as follows, and then pressing “Enter”:
java -jar /opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/trimmomatic-0.39.jar PE -phred33 -trimlog log.txt mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_1.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedS_1.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_2.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedS_2.fastq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:/opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/adapters/NexteraPE-PE.fa:2:30:10 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:36

What are we doing when we run this?

  • Calling Trimmomatic (java -jar /opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/trimmomatic-0.39.jar)
  • Telling Trimmomatic that we have paired-end (PE) reads (PE)
  • Telling Trimmomatic that our Illumina reads have ASCII_BASE 33 quality scores and not the ASCII_BASE 64 quality scores used by very old Illumina platforms (-phred33)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to create a log file named log.txt (-trimlog log.txt)
  • Giving Trimmomatic the path to our forward reads in fastq.gz format (mystery_salmonella_A_1.fastq.gz)
  • Giving Trimmomatic the path to our reverse reads in fastq.gz format (mystery_salmonella_A_2.fastq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed forward read pairs that it outputs (we can technically name this file anything, but let’s call it mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_1.fastq.gz; the _1.fastq.gz suffix lets us know that the file contains forward reads, while trimmedP lets us know that these reads are trimmed read pairs)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed forward unpaired reads that it outputs (similar to before, we can name this anything, but let’s call it mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedS_1.fastq.gz because they are trimmed forward SINGLE [unpaired] reads)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed reverse read pairs that it outputs (to be consistent, mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_2.fastq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic what we want to name the trimmed reverse unpaired reads that it outputs (to be consistent, mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedS_2.fastq.gz)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove Illumina Nextera paired-end adapters, with the adapter sequences provided in the NexteraPE-PE.fa file (ILLUMINACLIP:/opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/adapters/NexteraPE-PE.fa:2:30:10)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove leading low quality or N bases below quality 3 (LEADING:3)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to remove trailing low quality or N bases below quality 3 (TRAILING:3)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to scan each read with a 4-base wide sliding window, cutting when the average quality per base drops below 15 (SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15)
  • Telling Trimmomatic to drop reads less than 36 bases long (MINLEN:36)

  1. Once Trimmomatic is finished, let’s take a look at the sizes of our fastq.gz files to get a rough idea of the effect trimming had on our genome. To do this, we can use ls with the -l and -h options to list our files and their respective sizes in human-readable format; we can additionally supply *.fastq.gz after the command, which allows us to only list files ending in .fastq.gz:

    ls -lh *.fastq.gz

2.5 Assessing the quality of trimmed Illumina reads with FastQC

  1. Now let’s run FastQC on our trimmed paired reads (forward and reverse):

    perl /opt/FastQC/fastqc mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_1.fastq.gz mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_2.fastq.gz

  2. Follow the instructions for copying the resulting html files to your local computer (See Section 2.3, Step #4, but replace the filenames for the forward and reverse reads with mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_1_fastqc.html and mystery_salmonella_A_trimmedP_2_fastqc.html, respectively), and open them. Has the quality of your reads improved?

3.3 Writing simple scripts in Bash

We used Trimmomatic to trim raw Illumina reads associated with a bacterial isolate; however, what if we had 10 isolates? 100? 1,000? Rather than typing in the command to run Trimmomatic on each set of paired-end reads, we can use Bash to write a simple script that loops through our read pairs, trimming each set:

#!/bin/bash

for f in *_1.fastq.gz
do
java -jar /opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/trimmomatic-0.39.jar PE -phred33 -trimlog ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimlog.txt $f ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_2.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedP_1.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedS_1.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedP_2.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedS_2.fastq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:/opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/adapters/NexteraPE-PE.fa:2:30:10 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:36;
done

We’ll go through this line-by-line:

#!/bin/bash

This line is called a shebang; the part after #! tells the operating system to invoke the Bash shell to execute the commands in the script.

for f in *_1.fastq.gz
do

We’re telling the computer to loop through all files ending in _1.fastq.gz (i.e., each file containing forward reads), running the command(s) that follow. We will use the variable f to represent each _1.fastq.gz file (i.e., each file containing forward reads for each genome).

java -jar /opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/trimmomatic-0.39.jar PE -phred33 -trimlog ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimlog.txt $f ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_2.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedP_1.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedS_1.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedP_2.fastq.gz ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_trimmedS_2.fastq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:/opt/Trimmomatic-0.39/adapters/NexteraPE-PE.fa:2:30:10 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:36;

This is the Trimmomatic command that we used before, but with a couple of key differences; for forward reads, we specify $f. This tells Bash to run the command with whichever forward read file is stored as the variable f. For our reverse reads, we specify ${f%_1.fastq.gz}_2.fastq.gz. This tells the computer to take all of the text up to _1.fastq.gz for our current variable f, and append the suffix _2.fastq.gz; so basicaly, what we’re doing is specifying the reverse reads that match our forward reads, assuming they are identically named except for the _1.fastq.gz and _2.fastq.gz suffix. The same logic applies for the names of the output files, as well as the logfile. Bash runs this command for each set of reads, executing Trimmomatic on each.

done

We’re telling Bash that this is the end of our loop.

To run the script, we can save it as something, such as trimmomatic.sh (where .sh indicates that it is a shell script written in Bash), move it to the directory in which we have all of our paired-end reads, and enter the following command:

sh trimmomatic.sh

With this command, we tell the shell (sh, which in our case is Bash) to run the commands in our script.

FastQC conveniently lets us list all of the files we want to run in a single command; however, just for fun, a user could write a simple loop, similar to the Trimmomatic script shown above, to run the fastqc command on each file containing Illumina reads. Using what you know about FastQC and Bash, try writing a simple Bash script to accomplish this. Which is faster for paired-end reads from a single bacterial isolate…running FastQC with a single command (as done in the main activity), or running FastQC in your loop?

5 Linux Cheat Sheet

Print the contents of a file:

cat <path/filename>

Move to a different directory:

cd <path>

Move up one directory:

cd ..

Move to the root directory:

cd /

Move to your home directory:

cd ~

Copy the source file to the destination:

cp <source> <destination>

Copy the source directory to the destination:

cp -r <source> <destination>

Download a file from an online source (curl):

curl filename

Show disk usage:

df

Show directory space usage:

du

Find all instances of file in path with given name:

find <path> -name <pattern>

Show memory and swap usage in human-readable format:

free -h

Print all appearances of pattern in file:

grep <pattern> <path/filename>

Count all appearances of pattern in file:

grep -c <pattern> <path/filename>

Gzip file(s):

gzip path/filename

Decompress gzipped file(s):

gzip -d path/filename.gz

Print the first 10 lines of a file:

head <path/filename>

Print system hostname:

hostname

List the given path:

ls <path>

List the given path, showing permissions, size, and modification dates in human readable format:

ls -lh <path>

List the given path, showing permissions, size, and modification dates in human readable format, sorting by filesize from largest to smallest:

ls -lhS <path>

List the given path, showing permissions, size, and modification dates in human readable format, sorting by filesize from smallest to largest:

ls -lhSr <path>

View the manual for a command (press q to exit manual):

man <command>

Create a directory:

mkdir <path/directory_name>

Move the source file or directory to the destination:

mv <source> <destination>

Print working directory (where am I?):

pwd

Remove a file:

rm <path/filename>

Remove an empty directory:

rm -d <path/directory>

Remove a non-empty directory (use with caution!):

rm -r <path/directory>

Secure copy a file from remote server to the dir directory on your machine:

scp user@host:file dir

Secure copy a file from your machine to the dir directory on a remote server:

scp file user@host:dir

Secure copy the directory foo from remote server to the directory bar on your machine:

scp -r user@host:foo bar

Execute a shell script, script.sh:

sh script.sh

Connect to host as user:

ssh user@host

Print the last 10 lines of a file:

tail <path/filename>

Create a tar file, file.tar:

tar -cf file.tar path/directory

Extract a tar file, file.tar:

tar -xf file.tar

Create a gzipped tar file, file.tar.gz:

tar -czf file.tar.gz path/directory

Extract a gzipped tar file, file.tar.gz:

tar -xzf file.tar.gz

Download a file from an online source (wget):

wget filename

Print who you are logged in as:

whoami
